initial_story:
The Eurovision Song Contest is just around the corner and this year, it's taking place in Malmo, Sweden.

You can find out all about the event right here.

The UK's entry for 2024 is Olly Alexander who'll be performing his song, Dizzy.

But how's he feeling ahead of the big night, where he'll perform in front of 200 million people!

De-Graft sat down with him to find out all about his preparation for the competition.

The Eurovision Song contest Grand Final will be shown on BBC One and iPlayer on Saturday 11 May.
stories: Olly Alexander is feeling "nervous but excited" ahead of his performance at the Eurovision Song Contest, and has been putting in the hard work to make sure he's ready for the big night.
He's been rehearsing his song, "Space Man", for hours on end, perfecting every note and movement, and has even been working with a choreographer to make sure his dance routine is on point.

The crowd is going wild as he takes the stage, his bright blue suit and matching platform shoes making him look like a true rockstar. He adjusts his mic stand, takes a deep breath, and launches into the opening chords of "Space Man", his powerful voice soaring as he belts out the lyrics. The dance routine is flawless, his moves precise and energetic, and the audience is completely entranced.

The spotlight shines down on him, highlighting his slicked-back hair and perfectly chiseled features as he works the crowd like a seasoned pro. The music builds to a frenetic pace, and he spins and leaps across the stage, his platform shoes making him seem even taller and more imposing. The crowd is on its feet, singing along to every word and waving their arms in the air as he reaches the climax of the song.

As the final notes fade away, the crowd erupts into cheers and applause, and he takes a triumphant bow, his eyes scanning the sea of adoring faces. The lights dim, and the stagehands rush to set up the next act, but he lingers, soaking up the adoration, his chest heaving with exertion. Suddenly, a spotlight shines down on him once more, and he raises his arms to the crowd, basking in the applause as the words "ENCORE!" echo through the venue.

He grins, his eyes sparkling with excitement, as the crowd begins to chant his name, demanding more. The band launches into a blistering rendition of his hit single, and he launches into the vocals, his voice soaring as he works the crowd into a frenzy. The energy in the room is electric, and he feeds off it, pouring every ounce of passion and energy into the performance.

As the song comes to a close, the crowd erupts into cheers and applause, and he takes a triumphant bow, his chest heaving with exertion. He scans the sea of faces, his eyes locking onto the familiar figure of his lead guitarist, who's grinning from ear to ear. The guitarist gives him a thumbs-up, and he flashes a quick smile before turning back to the audience, his eyes gleaming with a challenge. "You want more?" he yells, his voice echoing off the walls of the arena. The crowd roars its approval, and he launches into the opening chords of his next song, the music swirling around him like a vortex of pure energy.

The lights dim, and the stage is bathed in a pulsing red glow as the opening riffs of "Electric Storm" blast through the speakers. The crowd surges forward, hands raised in the air as the band launches into the song's driving beat. He sings with reckless abandon, his voice soaring above the music as he dances across the stage, his guitar slung low and loose. The energy is electric, and the crowd is completely entranced, lost in the music and the moment.

The sweat-drenched crowd is a sea of bobbing heads and flailing limbs, as if possessed by the raw power of the music. The band's lead singer, a whirlwind of energy and charisma, spins and leaps across the stage, his mic stand a mere accessory to his wild abandon. The guitarist, a master of his craft, shreds with reckless precision, his fingers flying across the fretboard as he conjures up a maelstrom of sound. The drummer, a human dynamo, pounds out the rhythm with a ferocity that threatens to shake the very foundations of the venue.

As the music reaches a frenzied crescendo, the crowd surges forward, a tidal wave of humanity crashing against the barrier that separates them from the stage. The singer's voice soars above the din, a primal scream of joy and release, as the guitarist's notes seem to ignite the air around him, sending sparks flying in all directions. The drummer's sticks are a blur, a whirlwind of motion that threatens to consume him whole, yet he remains steadfast, a rock at the center of the maelstrom.

The bassist's fingers dance across the fretboard, a mesmerizing display of dexterity and power, as the crowd's collective energy reaches a fever pitch. Sweat drips from the singer's brow, his eyes closed in rapture, as the music becomes one with his very being. The guitarist's face is a mask of concentration, his hair a wild tangle of curls, as he coaxes every last drop of emotion from his instrument. The drummer's sticks crash down in a final, triumphant flourish, and the music comes to a halt, leaving the crowd gasping for breath.

The silence is palpable, a heavy blanket of anticipation that hangs in the air as the band members stand frozen, their instruments still reverberating with the final notes. The crowd, still reeling from the intensity of the performance, slowly begins to stir, their applause building in a slow, deliberate crescendo. The singer's eyes snap open, his gaze sweeping the sea of faces before him, his chest heaving with exertion. The guitarist's curls are now a wild tangle of sweat-drenched locks, his face a map of concentration and exhaustion. The bassist's fingers still hover above the fretboard, as if reluctant to relinquish the magic that has just transpired.

As the applause reaches a fever pitch, the drummer's hands slowly release their grip on the sticks, his eyes never leaving the crowd as he absorbs the adoration. The singer's gaze lingers on the sea of faces, his eyes locking onto a few familiar ones in the front row, his face creasing into a weary smile. The guitarist's wild curls begin to droop, his eyes squinting against the bright lights as he surveys the room, his chest still heaving with exertion. The bassist's fingers finally release their hold on the fretboard, his eyes drifting shut as he savors the moment, the music still echoing in his mind.

As the music fades away, the crowd's roar gradually subsides, replaced by the murmur of conversations and the rustling of clothing as people begin to file out of the venue. The drummer, still standing behind his kit, takes a deep breath and lets it out slowly, his eyes never leaving the crowd as he tries to process the rush of adrenaline that still courses through his veins. The singer, meanwhile, makes his way offstage, his weary smile still plastered on his face as he scans the room for his bandmates. The guitarist, still seated on his stool, slowly raises his head, his eyes squinting against the bright lights as he tries to shake off the exhaustion that threatens to overwhelm him. The bassist, still lost in the music, slowly opens his eyes, his gaze drifting out into the crowd as he tries to make sense of the chaos that has just unfolded.

The roadies, already busy dismantling the equipment, glance up at the band members with a mix of admiration and exhaustion, their faces a testament to the long hours and hard work that went into making the show a success. The singer spots his guitarist, still seated on his stool, and makes his way over to him, clapping him on the back and saying something that makes the guitarist crack a tired smile. The drummer, still standing behind his kit, takes a step forward, his eyes never leaving the crowd, as if trying to memorize every face, every expression, every moment of the night. The bassist, finally coming back to reality, looks around at the chaos of the venue, taking in the scattered bodies, the discarded merchandise, and the lingering smell of sweat and music.

As the bassist takes in the scene, he can't help but feel a sense of pride and accomplishment wash over him. He looks over at his bandmates, who are all chatting and laughing with the roadies, and feels grateful to be a part of this team. The singer, still grinning from his conversation with the guitarist, catches his eye and raises his hand in a silent "thank you" before turning back to the task of packing up his gear. The drummer, still lost in thought, takes another step forward, his eyes scanning the crowd as if searching for someone. The roadies, sensing that the band is ready to move on, begin to load up the trucks, their movements efficient and practiced. As the venue starts to clear out, the bassist takes one last look around, committing the moment to memory.

The smell of sweat and stale beer lingers in the air as he takes a deep breath, savoring the atmosphere of the emptying room. He glances down at his instrument, still plugged in and humming softly, and feels a pang of nostalgia for the energy and chaos that had filled the space just hours before.

The memories of raucous laughter and shouted lyrics still echoed in his mind, mingling with the faint scent of spilled whiskey and worn denim. He strums a few tentative chords, and the familiar notes seem to conjure up the ghosts of past performances, the sweat-drenched crowds and the endless requests for encores.

As he played, the dimly lit room around him began to fade away, replaced by the vibrant colors and pulsating energy of the stage, the roar of the crowd and the rush of adrenaline that had once coursed through his veins like lifeblood. He closed his eyes, letting the music transport him back to those heady days, when the world had seemed so much bigger and his dreams had seemed within reach.

The memories came flooding back, like a tidal wave crashing over him, washing away the dust and disillusionment of the years that had passed. He remembered the thrill of performing live, the rush of endorphins as he lost himself in the music, and the sense of connection he felt with the audience as they sang along to every word.

He remembered the smell of sweat and smoke, the feel of the guitar strap digging into his shoulder, and the way the lights seemed to blur together into a kaleidoscope of color as he closed his eyes and let the music take over.

As the notes faded away, he opened his eyes to find himself back in the dimly lit room, the familiar contours of his childhood home looming around him. The memories came flooding back, like a tidal wave crashing against the shores of his mind.

The scent of old books and stale air enveloped him, transporting him back to a time when life was simpler, when his biggest worry was what game to play next or what book to read. He remembered the creaky floorboards beneath his feet, the worn-out armchair in the corner, and the way the sunlight streaming through the window would dance across the walls, casting a warm glow over everything.

As he stood there, nostalgia washing over him like a gentle wave, he could almost hear the soft hum of his mother's voice, reading aloud from a favorite novel, her words weaving a spell of wonder and magic around him. The memories came flooding back, each one more vivid than the last: the way his father would laugh, his eyes twinkling with mischief, as he told tales of adventure and bravery; the sound of his siblings' giggles, as they played hide-and-seek behind the bookshelves; and the feel of his own small hands, tracing the spines of the books, as he searched for the perfect story to lose himself in.

The scent of old books and fresh paper wafted up, transporting him back to those lazy summer afternoons, spent curled up on the worn velvet armchair, surrounded by the comforting silence of the library. He could almost smell the faint tang of his mother's perfume, lingering on the pages of her favorite novels, and feel the soft brush of her hair against his cheek as she leaned in to whisper a secret. The memories swirled around him, a kaleidoscope of color and sound, and he felt his heart swell with a deep longing to be back in that place, surrounded by the people and things he loved.

As he stood there, lost in the nostalgia of it all, the librarian's gentle voice broke the spell, "Can I help you find something, sir?" she asked, her eyes crinkling at the corners as she smiled. He blinked, feeling a pang of embarrassment at being caught in his reverie, and shook his head, "No, no, I'm fine. Just...just enjoying the atmosphere." The librarian nodded understandingly, her eyes never leaving his, and he felt a sense of gratitude towards her for not pushing him to reveal more.

The librarian's gaze lingered on his for a moment longer, then she nodded and returned to her task, leaving him to his thoughts. He took a deep breath, feeling the familiar scent of old books and dusty air fill his lungs, and began to wander the shelves, running his fingers over the spines of the volumes as he went. As he walked, the sounds of the library grew louder - the rustle of pages, the soft murmur of hushed conversations, the occasional beep of a computer - and he felt himself becoming one with the place, a part of the quiet, studious world that existed within these walls.

The silence was a balm to his soul, a refuge from the chaos that had been his life for so long. He had always found solace in the library, where the only drama was the occasional misplaced book or forgotten library card. He drifted from shelf to shelf, his eyes scanning the titles, his fingers tracing the letters on the spines. The words blurred together, but he didn't need to read them to know what they said. He knew the stories, the histories, the secrets that lay hidden within these pages.

As he wandered deeper into the stacks, the scent of old paper and leather bindings enveloped him, transporting him to a time when life was simpler, when the weight of the world was not so heavy on his shoulders. He stopped in front of a shelf dedicated to classic literature, his gaze settling on a worn copy of "Wuthering Heights". The memories came flooding back, of lazy summer afternoons spent reading by the lake, of whispered conversations with his best friend about the tortured souls of the Brontë sisters' characters.

The worn cover seemed to whisper secrets to him, and he felt a shiver run down his spine as he reached out to touch the embossed letters on the spine. Suddenly, he was transported back to those lazy summer days, the warm sun beating down on his skin as he lay on a blanket, the words of Emily Brontë's masterpiece swirling around him like the mist that shrouded the moors. He could almost hear the distant howl of the wind, feel the rough texture of the moorland grass beneath his fingers.

As he stood there, lost in the nostalgia of it all, the scent of damp earth and heather wafted up from the book, transporting him further back in time to the days when he'd spent hours poring over the pages, devouring the tragic tale of Heathcliff and Catherine. The memories came flooding back: the way the words had seemed to leap off the page, the way the characters had felt like old friends, the way the story had made him feel like he was a part of something much bigger than himself.

He remembered the countless nights he'd stayed up late, reading by the light of a lamp, the words blurring together as his eyes grew heavy, but he couldn't stop turning the pages, compelled by the dark and brooding world that Emily Brontë had created. And then, there were the days spent walking the moors, feeling the wind in his hair, the sun on his face, and the rain on his skin, just as Heathcliff and Catherine had done, as if he was reliving their story, their struggles, and their passions.

The moors had become a sanctuary for him, a place where he could escape the mundane routine of his daily life and lose himself in the wild beauty of the Yorkshire landscape. He'd often find himself standing at the edge of a precipice, gazing out at the seemingly endless expanse of heather and gorse, feeling the weight of the characters' emotions as if they were his own. And yet, despite the sense of connection he felt to the story, he couldn't shake the feeling that there was something missing, something that he couldn't quite put his finger on.

As he stood there, the wind whipping his hair into a frenzy, he felt a sudden jolt of recognition - it was the same feeling he got when he was reading a particularly well-crafted sentence, one that made him pause and re-read it multiple times, savoring the language and the emotions it evoked. He thought back to the first time he'd read the book, the way the words had come alive on the page, transporting him to a world of love, loss, and longing. And then, like a puzzle piece falling into place, he knew what was missing - the sense of wonder, of magic, that only a truly great book could evoke.

He felt a shiver run down his spine as he realized that the same sense of wonder was what had been missing from his own writing, the spark that had driven him to create in the first place, but had slowly begun to fade as the demands of his daily life took precedence.

As he sat there, lost in thought, the words of his favorite childhood book began to whisper themselves into his mind, the characters and worlds he had once loved so dearly now seeming to hold a strange and wistful allure, like a forgotten key that might unlock the door to his own creative potential once more.

The memories came flooding back, of lazy summer afternoons spent sprawled across the living room floor, surrounded by dog-eared pages and the sweet scent of fresh-cut grass, as he devoured the adventures of a brave young hero and his trusty steed, their exploits weaving a spell of wonder that had never truly broken.

His eyes would glaze over, lost in the world of Middle-earth, as the sunbeams streaming through the windows danced across the pages, illuminating the battles between good and evil, and the quiet moments of introspection that revealed the depth of the characters' souls.

As he turned the pages, the scent of old parchment and leather bindings wafted up, transporting him to the rolling green hills and misty mountains of the Shire, where hobbits lived simple, peaceful lives, unaware of the darkness gathering in the shadows.

The memories flooded back, of lazy summer days spent in the sun-dappled gardens of Bag End, of long conversations with Bilbo over a pipeful of Longbottom Leaf, of the warmth and comfort of the firelit rooms of the Prancing Pony.

Of the laughter and music that filled the air, of the stories and tales that flowed like the Brandywine River, of the sense of belonging and wonder that came with being in the Shire, where the cares of the world seemed to fade away like the morning mist on a summer's morning.

And of the warmth of the fire that crackled and spat on the hearth, of the smell of freshly baked bread wafting from the oven, and of the gentle rustle of leaves in the trees as the sun dipped low in the sky, casting a golden glow over the rolling hills and green pastures of the Shire, where the simple pleasures of life were savored and cherished.

It was a day like any other in the quiet village of Hobbiton, where the hobbits went about their daily routines, enjoying the beauty of nature and the comfort of their cozy homes, and yet, amidst the tranquility, a sense of excitement and anticipation hung in the air, for it was on this day that the annual Harvest Festival was to take place, a time of feasting and merriment, when the hobbits would gather together to give thanks for the bounty of the land and to celebrate the changing of the seasons.

The villagers were busy preparing for the festivities, decorating the town square with colorful streamers and lanterns, and the aroma of freshly baked bread and roasting meats wafted through the air, making everyone's mouth water in anticipation of the feast to come. In the midst of all the hustle and bustle, a small group of hobbits, led by the curious and adventurous Frodo Baggins, were making their way to the edge of the village, where they had heard rumors of a mysterious stranger who was said to be arriving in town that day, bringing with him tales of far-off lands and exotic treasures.

As they walked, the group of hobbits chatted excitedly among themselves, speculating about the stranger's identity and the stories he might tell. Frodo, ever the curious one, was practically bouncing with anticipation, his bright green eyes shining with excitement. Suddenly, a commotion at the edge of the village caught their attention, and they turned to see a dusty, worn-out figure emerging from the trees, his long coat flapping behind him like a dark cloud.

The stranger's eyes, sunken and weary, locked onto the group, and for a moment, no one spoke, as if the very air was thick with unspoken questions. Then, with a slow, deliberate movement, he raised a hand, and a battered leather satchel slumped from his grasp, its worn straps creaking in protest.

The group's collective gaze followed the satchel as it thudded onto the dusty ground, sending up a small cloud of dirt and debris. The stranger's eyes never left theirs, his gaze burning with a quiet intensity that seemed to bore into their very souls.

The air was heavy with tension as the group held its collective breath, the only sound the soft rustling of the stranger's worn leather gloves as he reached for the satchel's worn straps. His fingers closed around them like a vice, and he slowly pulled the satchel open, revealing a jumble of strange and exotic items that seemed to glow with an otherworldly light in the fading sunlight.

As the group's eyes widened in unison, the stranger's gaze swept over them, his eyes narrowing into slits as he seemed to size them up, his mind working with a calculating precision that made the hairs on the back of their necks stand on end. One of the group members, a young woman with a mop of curly brown hair, took a step forward, her hand reaching out as if drawn to the satchel's contents, and the stranger's grip on the straps tightened, his voice low and menacing as he spoke a single word: "Don't."

The group froze, their eyes locked on the stranger's face, as the young woman's hand hovered inches from the satchel's worn leather. The air was thick with tension, the only sound the soft creaking of the straps as the stranger's grip remained unyielding. The woman's eyes, wide with curiosity, never left the satchel, and the stranger's gaze never wavered, his eyes burning with an intensity that seemed to pierce right through her.
